Paragraph: (1) "William!". (2) Mrs. Brown called out, looking very tired. (3) "You've been playing that noisy game again!". (4) William, who was all dusty and messy, with his tie crooked and his knees scraped, looked up. (5) "No, I wasn't playing the game you told me not to," he said, trying to explain. (6) "You said not to play 'Lions and Tamers.' (7) I didn't play that game at all!". (8) Mrs. Brown sighed. (9) "Then what were you playing?". (10) she asked, trying to understand. (11) "We were playing 'Tigers and Tamers,'" William answered quickly. (12) "It's a totally different game.". (13) Mrs. Brown was confused. (14) "What do you do in 'Tigers and Tamers'?". (15) she asked, a bit suspicious. (16) William thought for a moment. (17) "Well, in 'Tigers and Tamers,' some of us pretend to be tigers and the others are tamers. (18) But it's different from 'Lions and Tamers,'" he insisted.

 (19) Mrs. Brown wasn't convinced. (20) "It sounds the same to me," she said. (21) "But it's not!". (22) William said firmly. (23) "A lion isn't the same as a tiger. (24) They're different!". (25) Mrs. Brown decided right then. (26) "Okay, William, now you're not to play 'Tigers and Tamers' either," she told him.

 (27) William looked surprised. (28) "But I've been so clean today," he protested. (29) "I washed my face when I woke up and again for dinner, just like you told me!".

 (30) Mrs. Brown couldn't help but smile a little, even though she was trying to be firm. (31) "Go wash up again, please," she said. (32) William knew he had to listen, so he headed off to clean up, still mumbling about tigers and lions not being the same.



