Book Title: East of the Sun and West of the Moon: Old Tales from the North

Book Author: Peter Christen Asbjørnsen

Paragraph: (1) One day, there was a loud, crashing noise as if the whole house was falling down.

 (2) "Ugh! (3) Ugh! (4) I smell humans in my house," growled the troll, sniffing around with his nine big noses.

 (5) A princess quickly said, "Oh, a raven dropped a human bone down the chimney earlier! (6) I tried to throw it out, but it kept coming back. (7) I finally buried it, and cleaned up, but maybe the smell is still here.".

 (8) "I definitely smell it," the troll replied.

 (9) The princess had an idea. (10) "Why don't you lay your heads in my lap and I'll scratch them? (11) The smell will go away while you sleep.". (12) The troll agreed and soon he was fast asleep, snoring loudly. (13) The princess then placed stools and cushions under his heads so she could sneak away.

 (14) A soldier tiptoed in quietly and struck the troll. (15) With one big swing, he chopped off eight of the troll's heads. (16) But the sword was too short to reach the last head, which woke up and roared.

 (17) "Ugh! (18) Ugh! (19) I smell a human!". (20) "Here I am!". (21) the soldier said bravely. (22) Before the troll could move, the soldier struck again, and the last head rolled away.

 (23) Imagine how happy the princesses were now that the troll was gone. (24) They no longer had to sit there scratching his heads. (25) They were so thankful to the soldier. (26) The youngest princess even tied her gold ring in his hair as a thank you gift.

 (27) They gathered as much gold and silver as they could carry and started their journey home.

 (28) When it was time, they pulled on a rope and a captain and a lieutenant helped pull up the princesses one by one.

 (29) However, the soldier didn't trust his friends fully. (30) He decided to test them by sending up a heavy lump of gold first. (31) When the gold was halfway up, the others cut the rope, and it crashed to the ground.

 (32) "Now we're rid of him," the friends said, thinking they had tricked the soldier.

 (33) They frightened the princesses and made them promise to say that they were the ones who saved them from the troll. (34) The princesses didn't want to lie, but they were too scared not to agree. (35) Especially the youngest princess felt really sad about this. (36) But they knew they had to stay safe, so they agreed, even though they didn't want to.



